    <h2>Section A: Attempt Two Questions</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>Define queuing system. Explain the Kendall’s notation for queuing system? What are the various performance measures in single server queuing System? Explain which of them determine system stability and how?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The line where the entities or customer wait is generally known as a queue. The combination of all entities in the system being served and waiting for service will be called a queueing system.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-10960 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/download-4.png?resize=416%2C191&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="416" height="191"></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Kendall&#8217;s Notation:</strong></span></p>
<p>Different notations are frequently used in the queuing system and are called Kendall Notations. Kendall Notation is the standard system used to describe and classify a queueing node. The Kendall Notation can be represented in the form A/B/C/N/K.</p>
<p>where A indicates arrival pattern, B indicates service pattern, c indicates the number of servers, D indicates queuing discipline, N indicates system capacity, and K indicates calling population.</p>
<p>The symbols used for the probability distribution for inter-arrival time,  and service time are, D for deterministic, M for exponential, and E<sub>k</sub> for Erlang distribution.</p>
<p>If parameters D, N &amp; K are not specified then, N = ∞ (infinity), K = ∞ (infinity), D = FIFO</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Example:</span></p>
<p>M/D/2/FIFO/5/∞, queuing system having exponential arrival pattern, deterministic service time, 2 servers, FIFO queuing discipline, the capacity of 5 customers, and infinite population.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Performance measured in Single Server Queuing System:</strong></span></p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">The various performance measures in a single server queuing system simulation are discussed below:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li style="font-weight: 400;">If Ta and Ts be the inter-arrival time and the mean service time then</li>
</ol>
<ul style="font-weight: 400;">
<li><b><strong>Arrival rate </strong></b>λ=1/Ta</li>
<li><b><strong>Service rate</strong></b> μ=1/Ts</li>
</ul>
<ol start="2">
<li style="font-weight: 400;">The ratio of the mean service time to the mean inter-arrival time is called traffic<b><strong> </strong></b><b><strong>intensity</strong></b>. i.e.  u=Ts/Ta</li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><b><strong>Server utilization: </strong></b>It consists of only the arrival that gets served. It is denoted by and defined as</li>
</ol>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">        ρ= λTs= λ/ μ (server utilization for a single server).</p>
<ol start="4">
<li style="font-weight: 400;">The probability of finding the service counter free is (1 – ρ) i.e there are zero customers in the service facility.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Define true random numbers and pseudo random numbers with its properties . The sequence of numbers 0.64, 0.50, 0.25, 0.58,0.72, 0.90 has been generated. Use KS Test with Da=0.050 => 0512 to determine if the hypothesis that they are uniformly distributed on interval [o, 1] can be rejected.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><h3>True Random Numbers:</h3>
<p>True random numbers are generated from inherently unpredictable physical processes or sources, such as radioactive decay, atmospheric noise, or the unpredictable nature of quantum phenomena.</p>
<p><strong>Properties:</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Unpredictability:</strong> True random numbers are fundamentally unpredictable due to their source being natural processes or phenomena.</li>
<li><strong>Uniformity:</strong> They exhibit uniform distribution, with each number having an equal probability of occurring.</li>
<li><strong>Independence:</strong> Each number generated is independent of the previous or subsequent numbers, as they are derived from inherently random processes.</li>
<li><strong>Non-repeatability:</strong> The sequence of numbers cannot be replicated or reproduced. There&#8217;s no pattern or algorithm to recreate the sequence.</li>
</ol>
<h3>Pseudo-Random Numbers:</h3>
<p>Pseudo-random numbers are generated using algorithms that produce sequences of numbers that simulate the properties of true random numbers, but are deterministically derived from an initial value.</p>
<p><strong>Properties:</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Deterministic:</strong> Generated from known algorithms and an initial value (seed), which means the sequence can be reproduced if the algorithm and seed are known.</li>
<li><strong>Uniformity:</strong> A good pseudo-random number generator produces numbers that are uniformly distributed within the range [0,1].</li>
<li><strong>Independence:</strong> Each number is usually independent of others in the sequence, mimicking independence like true random numbers.</li>
<li><strong>Repeatability:</strong> The sequence of numbers can be reproduced if the initial seed and algorithm are known, leading to possible repetition.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Second part:<br />
<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-28379" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/43298cb0-2e5a-4c84-b0f2-daf7e5a5bf21.jpg?resize=910%2C1070&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="910" height="1070"><br />
</strong></p>
