<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>What do you understand by dynamic mathematical model? Explain with example. Differentiate it with static mathematical model.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Mathematical model is the model which is composed of a symbols and logic. It describes the system using mathematical concepts. The mathematical model is used to explain the system and to study the effects of different components, and to make predictions about the behavior of the system.</p>
<p>Dynamic mathematical model allows change to system attributes with time or as a function of time.</p>
<p>They are time-variant and are represented by using differential equations.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<p>For instance, consider the<strong> simple harmonic oscillator</strong>—a mass attached to a spring. Its motion is described by a second-order differential equation:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-28227" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/Screenshot-2023-12-07-at-13.25.34.png?resize=314%2C92&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="314" height="92"></p>
<p>This equation showcases how the position of the mass (<span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">x</span></span></span></span></span>) changes over time, depicting the relationship between the mass&#8217;s acceleration and its displacement from equilibrium. Solving this equation provides functions for <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x(t)</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">x</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span></span> and <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">dxdt</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">d</span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">t</span></span></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">d</span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">x</span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> (position and velocity, respectively), enabling us to precisely anticipate where the mass will be and how fast it will be moving at any given time during its oscillation.</p>
<p>In essence, dynamic mathematical models provide a mathematical framework to comprehend and predict the behavior of systems that evolve or change with time, offering insights into how various components interact and evolve over a continuum rather than at a single, static instance.</p>
