<h2>Section B: Attempt Eight Questions.</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Describe the phases in simulation.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The various phases of simulation are:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Problem Formulation:</strong> Clearly state the problem</li>
<li><strong>Setting Objectives and overall project plan</strong>: See how should approach the problem.</li>
<li><strong>Model Conceptualization:</strong> Establish a reasonable model using appropriate modeling approach.</li>
<li><strong>Data Collection:</strong> Collect relevant data about the system being modeled such are arrival rate, service rate, arrival process and more.</li>
<li><strong>Model translation:</strong> Convert the model into a programming language</li>
<li><strong>Verification:</strong> Verify that the implemented model behaves as intended and matches the conceptual model.</li>
<li><strong>Validation:</strong> Validate the model by comparing its output with real-world data or known results.</li>
<li><strong>Experimental Designs:</strong> Design experiments to explore various scenarios and conditions. For example: How many runs? How long are the runs?</li>
<li><strong>Production rule and analysis:</strong> Now run the simulation and collect and analyze the output.</li>
<li><strong>Repetition:</strong> If necessary, repeat some required steps.</li>
<li><strong>Document and Report:</strong> Document the simulation model, noting assumptions, limitations, and methodology. Also, create reports or presentations to share findings and suggestions.</li>
<li><strong>Implementation:</strong> Implement the simulated system in real world real-world scenarios if applicable and deploy the simulation for ongoing use or refinement</li>
</ol>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain the concept of discrete event simulation. Explain poisson’s arrival pattern.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Discrete event simulation is a computational method used to model and analyze the behavior of complex systems where events occur at specific points in time. It involves modeling the system as a sequence of discrete events, each of which causes a change in the system&#8217;s state. These events occur at distinct, separate points in time, and the system&#8217;s state evolves based on these occurrences.</p>
<p data-sourcepos="15:1-15:34">Let us see a real world<strong> example: </strong></p>
<p data-sourcepos="15:1-15:34">Imagine a grocery store checkout.</p>
<ul data-sourcepos="17:1-21:0">
<li data-sourcepos="17:1-17:40">Each <strong>customer arrival</strong> is an event.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="18:1-18:69">The <strong>time between customer arrivals</strong> determines the time advance.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="19:1-19:69">As customers arrive, the <strong>queue length changes</strong> (state variable).</li>
<li data-sourcepos="20:1-21:0">When a cashier becomes available, a <strong>service completion event</strong> occurs, and the customer leaves the queue (state change).</li>
</ul>
<p data-sourcepos="22:1-22:43"><strong>By simulating this system with DES, we can:</strong></p>
<ul data-sourcepos="24:1-27:0">
<li data-sourcepos="24:1-24:49">Analyze the average waiting time for customers.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="25:1-25:44">Identify the need for additional cashiers.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="26:1-27:0">Optimize the checkout layout to improve efficiency.</li>
</ul>
<p data-sourcepos="3:1-3:139"><strong>Second part:</strong></p>
<p data-sourcepos="3:1-3:139"><strong>Poisson arrival pattern</strong> describes a random process where events occur independently and at a constant average rate. This means that:</p>
<ul data-sourcepos="5:1-5:124">
<li data-sourcepos="5:1-5:124"><strong>Events occur independently:</strong> The occurrence of one event does not influence the probability of another event occurring.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="6:1-6:171"><strong>Events occur at a constant average rate:</strong> The average number of events occurring in a given interval is constant, regardless of the specific location of the interval.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="6:1-6:171"></li>
</ul>
<p data-sourcepos="3:1-3:3">The probability of observing <strong>k</strong> arrivals in a time interval of length <strong>t</strong> is given by the following equation:</p>
<p data-sourcepos="5:1-5:20"><strong>P(k arrivals in t) = (λt)^k * e^(-λt) / k!</strong></p>
<p data-sourcepos="7:1-7:6">where:</p>
<ul data-sourcepos="9:1-9:46">
<li data-sourcepos="9:1-9:46"><strong>λ</strong> is the arrival rate (average number of arrivals per unit time).</li>
<li data-sourcepos="10:1-10:36"><strong>t</strong> is the time interval length.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="11:1-11:34"><strong>k</strong> is the number of arrivals.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="12:1-12:7"><strong>e</strong> is the base of the natural logarithm</li>
<li data-sourcepos="13:1-14:0"><strong>k!</strong> is the factorial of k</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Some applications of Poisson&#8217;s arrival pattern are :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Telecommunications:</strong> Modeling the arrival of packets in a computer network.</li>
<li><strong>Queuing Theory:</strong> Analyzing waiting times in queues such as customer arrivals at service centers, call centers, or queues in traffic systems.</li>
<li><strong>Probability and Statistics:</strong> Describing the occurrence of rare events, like accidents in a specific region over time.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain Monte Carlo simulation method with an example?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Monte Carlo simulation is a computational technique that uses random sampling to model and analyze complex systems or processes. It relies on the generation of random inputs to explore the behavior of a system, allowing for the estimation of outcomes and the assessment of associated uncertainties. The method is named after the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco, known for its games of chance and randomness.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Following are the three important characteristics of Monte-Carlo method:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Its output must generate random samples.</li>
<li> Its input distribution must be known.</li>
<li>Its result must be known while performing an experiment.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-28141" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/IMG_2845.jpg?resize=2048%2C1749&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="2048" height="1749"></p>
<p>We use random number generation method to determine the sample points that lie inside or outside the curve.</p>
<p>Let (x0, y0) be an initial guess for the sample point than from a linear congruential method of random number generation:</p>
<p><strong>Xi+1 = (axi+c) mod m </strong></p>
<p><strong>Yi+1 = (ayi+c) mod m </strong></p>
<p>Where a &amp; c are constants, m is the upper limit of generated random number.</p>
<p>If y&lt;=yi then increment n.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>Define the terms verification, calibration, validation and accreditation of models.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Verification, Validation, and Accreditation (VV&amp;A) are three interrelated but distinct processes that gather and evaluate evidence to determine whether a model or simulation should be used in a given situation and establishing its credibility.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Verification:</strong> This process aims to establish that the simulation has been correctly implemented according to its design and specifications.Verification focuses on the correctness of the simulation&#8217;s construction, evaluating its capabilities, algorithms, and structure. It assesses whether the software or model performs as intended and is free from programming errors or implementation mistakes.</li>
<li><strong>Validation:</strong> Validation examines whether the simulation realistically represents the real-world system it intends to emulate. It involves comparing the simulation&#8217;s outputs or behavior with empirical data, observations, or experimental results from the actual system.It ensures that the simulation meets the required degree of accuracy for its intended purpose.</li>
<li><strong>Accreditation:</strong> Accreditation involves providing formal assurance or certification of a simulation&#8217;s credibility and suitability for specific applications or uses.  This process evaluates the simulation&#8217;s correctness, ensuring that its data and algorithms are sound, robust, and properly implemented. Accreditation also considers usability factors like the training and experience of the users, the quality and appropriateness of the data used, and the control procedures applied to the simulation.</li>
<li><strong>Calibration:</strong> Calibration is the iterative process of comparing the model with real system, revising the model if necessary, comparing again, until a model is accepted (validated). It often involves modifying or setting parameters, measurements, or characteristics to achieve greater accuracy, reliability, or alignment with established references or empirical data.</li>
</ul>
</div>
