<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>Why is estimation methods used in simulation? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Estimation methods in simulation are vital because they allow us to derive meaningful insights and predictions even in scenarios where conventional assumptions, like stationary and mutually independent observations, don&#8217;t hold true. For instance, in queuing systems where observations are not stationary and mutually independent, using estimation methods becomes crucial.</p>
<p>In such cases, where correlations among observations are necessary for analysis, a technique called simulation run statistics is employed. For instance, consider a queuing system denoted by Kendall’s notation M/M/1/FIFO, aiming to measure the mean waiting time. Estimating this mean waiting time involves accumulating waiting times of successive entities and dividing the sum by the number of entities. However, in such systems, data can be autocorrelated, meaning one value affects subsequent values.</p>
<p>The challenge arises because the distribution in these systems might not remain stationary initially. For instance, when a simulation starts with the system in an initial idle state, early arrivals might receive quick service, causing deviations from the expected normal distribution. This initial bias impacts the sample means of early arrivals. However, as the simulation continues and the sample size increases while the run lengthens, the effects of this bias diminish, and the distribution tends towards a normal distribution again.</p>
<p>Estimation methods help manage these complexities by allowing us to approximate parameters despite non-stationary distributions and initial biases. They enable us to make informed decisions and draw conclusions from simulations, even in scenarios where traditional assumptions do not hold.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain the importance of elimination of initial bias during simulation.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p data-sourcepos="3:1-3:109">Initial bias, the mismatch between a simulation&#8217;s starting state and reality, can distort results, leading to misleading conclusions. Eliminating it is crucial for obtaining <strong>reliable and unbiased results</strong>.</p>
<p data-sourcepos="5:1-5:24"><strong>Why is it important?</strong></p>
<ul data-sourcepos="7:1-7:34">
<li data-sourcepos="7:1-7:34"><strong>Accuracy:</strong> Biased simulations lead to inaccurate estimates of crucial metrics, potentially leading to poor decisions and inefficient operations.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="8:1-8:61"><strong>Clear Insights:</strong> Initial bias can mask the system&#8217;s true behavior, hindering the identification of genuine patterns and relationships.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="9:1-9:114"><strong>Generalizability:</strong> Biased simulations are specific to their starting state and cannot be applied to different operating conditions, limiting their usefulness.</li>
</ul>
<p data-sourcepos="11:1-11:28"><strong>How can we eliminate it?</strong></p>
<ul data-sourcepos="13:1-16:0">
<li data-sourcepos="13:1-13:137"><strong>Set Unbiased Initial Conditions:</strong> Start the system in a state reflecting its real-world conditions, not an empty or arbitrary state.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="14:1-14:146"><strong>Identify and Eliminate Model Bias:</strong> Thoroughly examine the simulation model&#8217;s assumptions and algorithms to ensure they don&#8217;t introduce bias.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="15:1-16:0"><strong>Run Multiple Simulations:</strong> Explore a range of starting points to identify patterns and trends independent of initial bias, providing a comprehensive understanding of the system.</li>
</ul>
<p data-sourcepos="17:1-17:95">By eliminating initial bias, we ensure simulations accurately reflect reality, leading to:</p>
<ul data-sourcepos="19:1-19:20">
<li data-sourcepos="19:1-19:20"><strong>Reliable Results:</strong> Better-informed decisions in various fields.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="20:1-20:72"><strong>Clearer Insights:</strong> A deeper understanding of the system&#8217;s dynamics.</li>
<li data-sourcepos="21:1-22:0"><strong>Improved Efficiency:</strong> Optimized resource allocation and improved performance.</li>
</ul>
<p data-sourcepos="23:1-23:228">Eliminating initial bias is not just a technical detail; it&#8217;s essential for ensuring the validity and usefulness of simulations. It unlocks their true potential to improve our understanding and management of complex systems.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Workers come to a supply store at the rate of one every 6(+-) 2 minute. Their requisitions are processed by one of the two clerks who take 8 (+-) 2 minutes for each requisition. The requisitions are then passed to a single storekeeper who fills them one at a time, taking 6(+-)3 minutes for each. Draw GPSS Block diagram to simulate The above problem for 100 requisitions.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Here is the GPSS block diagram</p>
